    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.26.59-61_0001"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">59</fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        702 Sharp Building
                        Kansas City 6, Mo
                
                        March 7, 1958
                    </dateline>
                    
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>Dr. John <hi rend="caps">G.</hi> Neihardt,</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Route #7</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Columbia, Missouri</addrLine>
                    </address>
                
                    <salute>Dear Dr. Neihardt:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>My research on Old Fort Robinson, Nebraska has led me into contact with some very nice people through correspondence. Among them is Mr. Fred <hi rend="caps">B.</hi> Hackett, a member of the Chicago Posse of The Westerners Corral.</p>
                
                <p>Mr. Hackett I wrote to concerning Crazy Horse; and he responded by sending me a copy of an original manuscript entitled "History of Chief Crazy Horse", which he obtained from the late Rev. Joseph Eagle Hawk, son of He Dog, great friend of Crazy Horse.</p>
                
                <p>This manuscript contains He Dog's account of the Oglala Sioux especially his last days at Fort Robinson. It contains a wealth of interesting inisghts into the Indian's way of viewing history.</p>
                
                <p>Mr. Hackett also included a brochure containing a Calendar For Oglala Sioux Names For the Years From 1759 to 1908. When he asked me if I would like an additional copy of this material, I replied and said would he send copies of this material to you. I also asked him to include a reprint of a tin-type he obtained from Ellen Howard, daughter of Bat Garnier, old time scout and interpreter, and good friend of Crazy Horse. This tin-type is said to be of Crazy Horse<add>.</add></p>
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.26.59-61_0002"/>
                
                    <fw type="curatorial">60</fw>
                
                    <fw type="authorial">- 2 -</fw>  
                
                <p>I might explain to you that I have been carrying on intensive research for authentic material to use in writing a definitive, historical article on Fort Robinson and the year Crazy Horse came in. I am going at this project as though I were working on a paper for a Master's Degree; every statement or fact will have a footnote to give the source.</p>
                
                <p>I might say that having a high regard for historical accuracy and original research I have been exremely irritated by numerous articles in magazines on western history, because, the authors are obviously rehashing what someone else has said; or else, they are so lazy that rather than dig for information they will take what someone else has done and rewrite it but give substantially the same information.</p>
                
                <p>For example, occasional articles appearing in recent years on Hugh Glass are founded on material included in your "Song of Hugh Glass."</p>
                
                <p>But enough of this: March is here and soon "the rains will be over and gone, the flowers appear on the earth, the time of the singing of birds is come, and the voice of the turtle is heard in our land." Ah, to be alive so much that every sense is awakened to absorb the music of the outdoors, a grand, majestic symphony to thrill.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>With kindest regard to you and Mrs. Neihardt,</salute>
                
                    <salute>Your friend,</salute>
                
                    <signed>Thomas W. Wright</signed>
                
                    <signed>Thomas W. Wright</signed>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
            
            
